ce:section.ce:para:
The nanoparticle size distribution and polydispersity were determined via DLS analysis. This technique measures the hydrodynamic diameter of nanoparticles in solution. It gives information about the core particle along with any coated material on the particle and the solvent layer attached to the particle as it moves under the influence of Brownian motion [40]. The diameter of the nanoparticles ranges between 160 and 320 nm (Fig. 2
                           ), with an average value of 227.3 nm. The polydispersity value (PDI) of the nanocarrier is 0.24. According to former studies, PDI values lower than 0.3 are indicative of a monodisperse system, which is suitable for drug delivery purposes [41]. Therefore, the PDI value obtained in this study shows that the nanocarrier is monodisperse. Also, a single peak is observed in the size distribution obtained from DLS test, corroborating the uniformity and monodispersity of the nanosystem. PDI values for different nanocarriers recently developed for the delivery of model drugs such as CUR, quercetin, doxorubicin or 5-Fluorouracil are compared in Table 2
                           . The results obtained in this study are consistent with those reported earlier for CUR delivery such as chitosan/agarose/montmorillonite [13] and carboxymethyl cellulose/starch/reduced graphene oxide [31].
